      "type": "eq",
      "start": 8,
      "end": 28,
      "html": "<section class=\"slide eq\"><ul class=\"eq-lines\"><li id=\"imp8c9dago\" class=\" eq-item eq-title \" > Understanding the Square </li><li id=\"imp8c9dagp\" class=\" eq-item eq-math \" > $$ (a+b)^2 $$ </li><li id=\"imp8c9dagq\" class=\" eq-item eq-math \" > $$ = (a+b)(a+b) $$ </li><li id=\"imp8c9dagr\" class=\" eq-item eq-math \" > $$ = a(a+b) + b(a+b) $$ </li><li id=\"imp8c9dags\" class=\" eq-item eq-math \" > $$ = a^2 + ab + ab + b^2 $$ </li><li id=\"imp8c9dagt\" class=\" eq-item eq-math \" > $$ = a^2 + 2ab + b^2 $$ </li></ul><div class=\"eq-side-panel\"><div id=\"imp8c9dago-sp-1\" class=\"eq-explain-item hidden\" ><img src=\"eq.webp\" /></div><div id=\"imp8c9dago-sp-2\" class=\"eq-explain-item hidden\" > The exponent applies to the entire bracket. </div><div id=\"imp8c9dago-sp-3\" class=\"eq-explain-item hidden\" > The bracket behaves like one unit. </div><div id=\"imp8c9dago-sp-4\" class=\"eq-explain-item hidden\" > Students often square only one term. </div><div id=\"imp8c9dago-sp-5\" class=\"eq-explain-item hidden\" > (a+b)^2 \\neq a^2+b^2 </div><div id=\"imp8c9dago-sp-6\" class=\"eq-explain-item hidden\" > The whole bracket multiplies itself. </div><div id=\"imp8c9dagp-sp-1\" class=\"eq-explain-item hidden\" ><img src=\"box.webp\" /></div><div id=\"imp8c9dagp-sp-2\" class=\"eq-explain-item hidden\" > This expression represents repeated multiplication. </div><div id=\"imp8c9dagp-sp-3\" class=\"eq-explain-item hidden\" > The square means two identical brackets. </div><div id=\"imp8c9dagp-sp-4\" class=\"eq-explain-item hidden\" > (a+b)(a+b) </div><div id=\"imp8c9dagp-sp-5\" class=\"eq-explain-item hidden\" > Every term must eventually multiply. </div><div id=\"imp8c9dagq-sp-1\" class=\"eq-explain-item hidden\" ><img src=\"image.png\" /></div><div id=\"imp8c9dagq-sp-2\" class=\"eq-explain-item hidden\" > Rewrite before expanding. </div><div id=\"imp8c9dagq-sp-3\" class=\"eq-explain-item hidden\" > This keeps the structure visible. </div><div id=\"imp8c9dagq-sp-4\" class=\"eq-explain-item hidden\" > Expansion becomes easier to track. </div><div id=\"imp8c9dagq-sp-5\" class=\"eq-explain-item hidden\" > a(a+b)+b(a+b) </div><div id=\"imp8c9dagr-sp-1\" class=\"eq-explain-item hidden\" ><img src=\"force-intro.webp\" /></div><div id=\"imp8c9dagr-sp-2\" class=\"eq-explain-item hidden\" > Distribute carefully from left to right. </div><div id=\"imp8c9dagr-sp-3\" class=\"eq-explain-item hidden\" > Avoid skipping intermediate products. </div><div id=\"imp8c9dagr-sp-4\" class=\"eq-explain-item hidden\" > Every multiplication matters. </div><div id=\"imp8c9dagr-sp-5\" class=\"eq-explain-item hidden\" > a\\times a , a\\times b </div><div id=\"imp8c9dagr-sp-6\" class=\"eq-explain-item hidden\" > b\\times a , b\\times b </div><div id=\"imp8c9dags-sp-1\" class=\"eq-explain-item hidden\" ><img src=\"eq.webp\" /></div><div id=\"imp8c9dags-sp-2\" class=\"eq-explain-item hidden\" > All four products are now visible. </div><div id=\"imp8c9dags-sp-3\" class=\"eq-explain-item hidden\" > Nothing is hidden anymore. </div><div id=\"imp8c9dags-sp-4\" class=\"eq-explain-item hidden\" > This is the expanded form before simplification. </div><div id=\"imp8c9dags-sp-5\" class=\"eq-explain-item hidden\" > ab+ab </div><div id=\"imp8c9dags-sp-6\" class=\"eq-explain-item hidden\" > The middle terms are identical. </div><div id=\"imp8c9dagt-sp-1\" class=\"eq-explain-item hidden\" ><img src=\"box.webp\" /></div><div id=\"imp8c9dagt-sp-2\" class=\"eq-explain-item hidden\" > Combine like terms carefully. </div><div id=\"imp8c9dagt-sp-3\" class=\"eq-explain-item hidden\" > Two copies of ab become 2ab. </div><div id=\"imp8c9dagt-sp-4\" class=\"eq-explain-item hidden\" > ab+ab=2ab </div><div id=\"imp8c9dagt-sp-5\" class=\"eq-explain-item hidden\" > This identity appears throughout algebra. </div></div></section>",
